          "body": "The chapter's longest section (6:27-36) is the love-of-enemies ethic, structured as four imperatives (love, do good, bless, pray — 6:27-28), four illustrations (turn the cheek, give the shirt, give to the asker, do not demand repayment — 6:29-30), the Golden Rule (6:31), three rhetorical tests with 'sinners' (6:32-34), and a climactic command (6:35-36). The logic is theological, not pragmatic: **love your enemies… and you will be sons of the Most High; for He Himself is kind to ungrateful and evil men** (6:35). Sonship is demonstrated by family resemblance — the Father is kind to the ungrateful (common grace), so the son is too. The section closes with the controlling summary: **Be merciful, just as your Father is merciful** (6:36). Luke's word *oiktirmon* is sharper than 'compassionate' — it is the gut-moved mercy that acts."
